{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"278e5d69-d61c-4ccb-9e98-9f0fbae11311","content":"Here's the recommended approach:\n\n### 1. Get a shell into the container\n```bash\nkubectl exec -it <pod-name> -- powershell\n```\n\n### 2. Install `dotnet-trace` (if not already present)\n```powershell\ndotnet tool install --global dotnet-trace\n```\n\n### 3. Find the process ID\n```powershell\ndotnet-trace ps\n```\n\n### 4. Collect the trace\n```powershell\ndotnet-trace collect -p <PID> --profile cpu-sampling --duration 00:00:30\n```\n\nThis writes a `.nettrace` file you can analyze in **Visual Studio** or **PerfView**.\n\n### Tips for Windows containers\n- If `dotnet tool` isn't available, download `dotnet-trace` as a [standalone .exe](https://aka.ms/dotnet-trace/win-x64).\n- To copy the trace off the pod:\n  ```bash\n  kubectl cp <pod>:<path>/trace.nettrace ./trace.nettrace\n  ```\n- If the container lacks the .NET SDK, you can alternatively use **PerfView** or **dotnet-monitor** (deploy as a sidecar) for always-on collection without modifying the app image.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"92a8500e-b345-458b-b53d-22d964338376","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking for guidance on collecting a performance trace from a .NET 8 application running in a Windows container on Kubernetes. This is a knowledge/advisory question, not a code task. I'll provide a concise answer.","outputTokens":360},"id":"8401d060-ca19-46d6-adbf-9f2f4fe7414f","timestamp":"2026-04-04T00:43:08.870Z","parentId":"c3a77aff-9420-4d26-9290-55d39caf6048"}
